   <widget class="QTextEdit" name="ust2">
    <property name="enabled">
     <bool>false</bool>
    </property>
    <property name="geometry">
     <rect>
      <x>110</x>
      <y>160</y>
      <width>411</width>
      <height>521</height>
     </rect>
    </property>
    <property name="styleSheet">
     <string notr="true">
    QTextEdit {
        background: transparent;
        font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;
        font-size: 10pt;
        border: none;
    }

</string>
    </property>
    <property name="html">
     <string>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;
&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;meta name=&quot;qrichtext&quot; content=&quot;1&quot; /&gt;&lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style&gt;&lt;/head&gt;&lt;body style=&quot; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;&quot;&gt;
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot; style=&quot; margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:11pt; color:#000000;&quot;&gt;In 1896, when the                                    erupted in full force, the Spanish authorities sought to silence those they viewed as instigators or sympathizers of the uprising. Rizal, despite his non-involvement in the immediate planning or execution of the revolution, was accused of being part of the conspiracy. He was arrested and charged with                 ,                  , and &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot; style=&quot; margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:11pt; color:#000000;&quot;&gt;              —charges based primarily on his association with the Katipunan and his subversive writings. Although there was no direct evidence linking him to the revolutionaries or any violent acts, the Spanish authorities were determined to eliminate the threat he posed to their colonial rule.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot; style=&quot; margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:11pt; color:#000000;&quot;&gt;Rizal was tried in a&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:11pt; font-weight:600; color:#000000;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:11pt; color:#000000;&quot;&gt;military court, which was widely regarded as a mock trial, lacking due process and fair representation. The proceedings were quick and designed to reach a predetermined outcome—&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:11pt; font-weight:696; color:#000000;&quot;&gt;Rizal’s execution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:11pt; color:#000000;&quot;&gt;. His defense had little chance against the political motivations of the Spanish government, which saw him as a symbol of the burgeoning Filipino nationalist movement. Despite his intellectual opposition to violent revolution, Rizal was found guilty, and the court sentenced him to death&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; color:#000000;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;</string>
    </property>
   </widget>
